[
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275932\">Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Composing.20exponential.20objects/near/229712264\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"277473\">Morgan Rogers (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Composing.20exponential.20objects/near/229706666\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>In what context? You'll notice that when you write out the correspondence defining an adjunction, the left adjoint functor appears on the left of the arrow (assuming it's pointing from left to right). That is, an adjunction <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">L \\dashv R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> give a correspondence between morphisms <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>L</mi><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">LX \\to Y</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span> and morphisms <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>R</mi><mi>Y</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X \\to RY</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.22222em;\">Y</span></span></span></span>.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I just noticed that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊣</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dashv</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span></span></span></span> looks like an arrow <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>→</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\to</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.36687em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span></span></span></span>, whose direction is the correct one (from the left adjoint to the right adjoint)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>This makes me wonder, does anyone know who invented the symbol <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊣</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dashv</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span></span></span></span> (was it Kan?), and why they chose that symbol? Is it supposed to have any relation to the turnstile from logic, or was it just a random symbol? Maybe it was used for adjoints in linear algebra or somewhere else, earlier than adjoint functors?</p>",
        "id": 229719961,
        "sender_full_name": "Jules Hedges",
        "timestamp": 1615401877
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I've never seen <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊣</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\dashv</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span></span></span></span> in linear algebra.</p>",
        "id": 229722409,
        "sender_full_name": "Joe Moeller",
        "timestamp": 1615402774
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Mmh I'd be surprised if it's not related to the logicians' <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊢</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\vdash</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊢</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 229723414,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1615403083
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The notation is introduced in the Kan’s paper on adjoint functors. The story goes that Eilenberg suggested the name adjoint because of some analogy with adjoint operators in functional analysis. So I’m guessing the notation comes from the notation for orthogonality in functional analysis</p>",
        "id": 229724829,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1615403583
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>make sense</p>",
        "id": 229725789,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1615403911
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(we have a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">¬</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\neg</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">¬</span></span></span></span> Kan emoj, but not a Kan one)</p>",
        "id": 229725819,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1615403927
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess because we can just assume that everything is a Kan extension anyway</p>",
        "id": 229727926,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1615404665
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Was it originally <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">⊥</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\bot</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">⊥</span></span></span></span> in a diagram?</p>",
        "id": 229728339,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1615404797
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"275932\">Matteo Capucci (he/him)</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/History.20of.20.24.24.5Cdashv.24.24/near/229725819\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>(we have a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">¬</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\neg</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.43056em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">¬</span></span></span></span> Kan emoj, but not a Kan one)</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>That's because everything is assumed by default to be a Kan extension.</p>",
        "id": 229728468,
        "sender_full_name": "Nathanael Arkor",
        "timestamp": 1615404844
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I.e,</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\"><pre><span></span><code> /--F--v\nA   ⊥   B\n ^--G--/\n</code></pre></div>",
        "id": 229728639,
        "sender_full_name": "James Wood",
        "timestamp": 1615404901
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>No. In the paper the notation is introduced sideways as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mo>⊣</mo><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">F \\dashv G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span aria-hidden=\"true\" class=\"katex-html\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.69444em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊣</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2777777777777778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.68333em;vertical-align:0em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 229729165,
        "sender_full_name": "Fawzi Hreiki",
        "timestamp": 1615405095
    }
]